Impact of Short-Snout Dragon reintroduction on Swedish Griffin abundance and spatial distribution

A report prepared for the Ministry of Magic

Allison Horst

10/31/2019

Introduction

In 2005, after a 425 year absence, 18 captively bred Swedish Short-Snout dragons were reintroduced to their historic habitat in the Scandinavian Mountains (Potter and Granger 2019). The subsequent increase in dragon population - reaching 284 dragons in 2019 - has been closely studied and widely reported (Weasley et al. 2019). Less understood is how dragon reintroduction has impacted the homerange and abundance of the endangered Swedish Griffin. Longbottom et al. predicted that dragon predation would decimate the Swedish Griffin population and shift their range to more protected forested areas at lower elevation (Longbottom et al. 2003). To date, however, dragon impacts on Griffin range and populations have not been explored. Here, we use data collected by the Fantastic Beasts Research Team to compare pre- and post-dragon population trends and spatial shifts for Swedish Griffins.

Figure 1. Swedish Griffin (left) and Swedish Short-Snout Dragon (right). Credit: Harry Potter wiki fandom.

Data and Methods

Data for Swedish Griffin abundance and location from 1984 - 2019 were collected and provided by the Fantastic Beasts Research Team. Griffin abundance (individuals) is estimated from annual aerial counts. Griffin location (latitude, longitude) is uploaded daily from GPS-enabled collars, and used to estimate range areas (km2). For more information on collection methods and spatial information, see metadata. Habitat shifts were based on aerial observation and GPS locations, and were binned for this report as “Grassland”, “Forest” or “Exposed rock”. Mean griffin range area (km2) was compared for pre-dragon (1984 - 2004) and post-dragon (2005 - 2019) periods by two-sample t-tests (\(\alpha\) = 0.05 throughout). Trends in Griffin abundance were compared before and after dragon reintroduction by linear regression. All analyses and figures were prepared using R software version 3.6.1.

Results

1. Effects of dragon reintroduction on griffin abundance

Trends in Swedish Griffin populations were compared for pre- and post-dragon reintroduction periods (Figure 1). Notably, and in contrast to predictions by Longbottom et al. (2003), the rate of Griffin population decline did not intensify following dragon reintroduction. In fact, while Griffin populations were decreasing sighly prior to dragon reintroduction (-2.4 \(\pm\) 3.6 individuals/year, mean \(\pm\) SE), since 2005 populations have grown on average by 1.2 \(\pm\) 6.3 individuals/year, though neither rate was significantly non-zero.

Figure 2. Swedish Griffin population before and after Short-Snout dragon reintroduction to the Scandinavian Mountains. Growth rates for pre-dragon griffin populations (black triangles; 1984 - 2004) and post-dragon griffin populations (gray circles; 2005 - 2019) were not significantly non-zero. Data: Fantastic Beasts Research Team.

2. Griffin shifts to lower elevation forests

While Swedish Griffin populations were not reduced following dragon reintroduction, a notable shift in Griffin habitat from exposed rocky slopes and snow fields to lower elevation forests has occurred since 2005 (Figure 3).

Figure 3. Proportions of griffins in three habitat types, 2005 - 2015. Griffin habitat (from aerial observations) was described as one of the following types: exposed rock and snow (light gray), low elevation forest (green), and grassland (gold). Total griffin counts by habitat survey year: n2005 = 354, n2010 = 332, and n2015 = 344. Data: Fantastic Beasts Research Team.

The proportion of griffins in grasslands remained relatively constant from 2005 - 2015, but dramatic shifts from exposed rocky slopes and snow fields to lower elevation forests were observed over the same period. In 2005, only 24.8 % of griffins were observed in lower elevation forests, compared to 61.3% in 2015. The increase in forest dwelling griffins coincided with a 3.5-fold decrease in the proportion of griffins observed in higher elevation exposed rock and snow field habitats. Snape (2017) proposes that the shift toward forested areas occurs as griffins seek shelter from flying dragons.

3. Impacts on griffin homerange size

Homerange areas (km2) were calculated from GIS data for collared griffins, and were compared for pre-dragon reintroduction (1983 - 2004; n = 418 collared griffins) and post-dragon reintroduction (2005 - 2019; n = 211 collared griffins).

Figure 4. Griffin homerange size before and after dragon reintroduction. Kernel density for pre-dragon (orange; n = 418) and post-dragon (dark green; n = 211) homerange size (km2) based on GIS data from collared griffins. Means for pre- and post-dragon periods (14.9 and 10.7 km2, respectively) are shown as dashed lines with in corresponding colors. Data: Fantastic Beasts Research Team.

Mean griffins homerange area decreased by 28.5% (from 14.9 and 10.7 km2) following dragon reintroduction (Figure 4), compared to those recorded for griffins in the pre-dragon (1984 - 2004) period, and the decrease was statistically significant (one-sample t-test, t(312.2) = 3.8, p = 0.014). Our results reinforce findings from an earlier study by Dumbledore et al. (2013), which reported decreased daily distance traveled and less variation in distance traveled for griffins in the presence of dragons.

Summary

  • Dragon reintroduction has not caused a decrease in Swedish Griffin populations (Figure 2)
  • Griffins are migrating to lower elevation forests, perhaps due to increased coverage and protection (Figure 3)
  • Griffin homerange areas are significantly smaller following dragon reintroduction (Figure 4)
